{{Quote|Well, son, aside from being of different stock – that's like the difference between blethyline and tarkaline; they look similar, but they’re different colors and sizes – aside from that, they don't have the same beliefs that we do. They are – less pure. They mix things together that we don’t mix together, and that includes who they, um, marry.''"<br />"''Uh-huh.''"<br />"''They aren't&hellip;bad people, just&hellip;different.''"<br />"''How, Da?''"<br />"''You know how you like saltnut butter on bread?''"<br />"''Yeah!''"<br />"''And how you also like bluefruit jam on bread?''"<br />"''Yeah&hellip;''"<br />"''But how if you mix saltnut butter and bluefruit jam on the same bread, you don't like it?''"<br />"''Uh-huh.''"<br />"''Well, that's how ensters and eksters are. They don’t mix together.''"<br />"''But, Da, people aren’t all the same, like saltnut butter and bluefruit jam, are they –''"<br />"''You'll understand this when you're older, Jos. Don't worry about it now.|Young [[Jos Vondar]] and his [[Parent/Legends|father]] on the differences between ensters and eksters|<ref name="JH">''[[MedStar II: Jedi Healer]]''</ref>}}
'''Ensterite''' was an old, long and traditional sociopolitical [[Corellian/Legends|Corellian]] label referring to beings [[Homeworld/Legends|native]] to the [[Corellian system/Legends|Corellian star system]]. <ref name="CSWE">{{CSWECite|I|237|enster}}</ref> Among their rituals, there was the heritage of the [[High Tongue]], an ancient and ceremonial [[Language/Legends|language]] generally spoken during the [[Purging Days]], yet it had fallen into disuse once [[Galactic Basic Standard/Legends|Galactic Basic]] was adopted as de facto lingua franca. A big part of an enster’s core belief system was that no [[Marriage/Legends|marriage]] could be made, much less consummated, outside the inhabitants of one’s own [[Star system/Legends|planetary system]]. The more extreme zealots restricted it even further, refusing to allow any affiliations offplanet. No exceptions were made. Yes, a young [[Gender/Legends|man]] or woman could go offworld, and yes, even the staunchest Ensterites might turn a blind eye if a son or a daughter somehow managed a temporary alliance with one of the [[Ekster]] – the “outsiders”. It was acceptable – barely; it wasn’t spoken of in polite circles, but it was done. Then the young, having got it out of their systems, were to return [[Corellia/Legends|home]], find a spouse from a proper enster family, and settle down. An enster could not bring an ekster home to meet their [[Parent/Legends|parents]]. It was simply not done – not unless one was willing to give up their clan and be renounced and ostracized for the rest of their life. Not to mention bringing shame and contempt on the immediate family.<ref name="BS">''[[MedStar I: Battle Surgeons]]''</ref> The social and personal invisibility did not diminished with [[Time/Legends|time]], or even with [[Death/Legends|death]].<ref name="JH"/>

Despite it all, but also because of it, certain practices that in principle should have been forbidden because of their moral ambiguity, started to spread widely and more frequently with [[Time/Legends|time]], and were not used to be spoken in polite gatherings. The most common one was [[Hustru fönster]], in which [[Ekster]] lovers were brought in secret to a traditional ensterite home as servants as a way to keep their true purpose hidden, thereupon, their ongoing affair with their respective ensterite master/lover under the wraps, and even [[Reproduction/Legends|siring]] [[Youngling/Legends|children]] that, in theory, are illegitimate but not exactly out of wedlock.<ref name="JH"/>

Amidst their notable clans, there were the [[Vondars]] and the [[Kersos]], which were intertwined with each other and mostly made out of [[Doctor/Legends|doctors]], especially surgeons. Among its most prominent members were [[Jos Vondar]] and [[Erel Kersos]], both of them surgeons who served the [[Grand Army of the Republic/Legends|Grand Army of the Republic]] during the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]] in the [[Republic Mobile Surgical Unit 7]] and abord the [[MedStar-class frigate/Legends|Medstar frigate]] on [[Drongar/Legends|Drongar]]. Both doctors, however, defied their ensterite tradition by taking [[Ekster]] spouses. Kersos was shunned for the rest of his life being declared a non-permes, while Vondar challenged his family – with the support of Kersos – after his service on Drongar. <ref name="JH"/>

